postcontent: I have a Mosin Nagant 7.62x54r.  I thought it would be cool to put a real scope on it, so I did.  It has a Leapers 5Th Gen 3-9x40 Rifle Scope that was custom attached to the gun.  The bolt had to be modified by a gunsmith to allow for a normal style scope (not long eye relief).  I bought a kit to do it, but a gunsmith had a better idea, and fabricated the parts.  Before I went to all this trouble I searched through hundreds of these rifles to find one with a perfect bore.  I wanted a real shooter.  After I had my shooter I then acquired all the accessories... The leather shoulder strap, the stripper clips, the original cleaning kits and tool set, even the bayonet, and a big hard case for it all.  I just don't have anywhere to shoot this bad boy.  I don't like having guns I don't shoot.  That defeats the fun.  If you need a good elk gun, this is your gun.  If you want a monster centerfire  rifle on  a budget, this is your gun.  I have decided that I want to get more .22lr stuff.  I want to trade for a good scoped .22lr tack driver.  I might consider a NAA Earl, or NAA belt buckle gun.  I would take money offers, but I warn you that I have a lot of time and money invested in this, and it is pretty cool.  Please only good offers or trades.  I'll throw in about 50 rounds of ammo too.

Colt Gold Cup National Match Series 80 MK IV with extra 'competition' modifications.   

.45 caliber with 5 inch barrel and blue finish.  Model 05870.

2) Gunsmith reduced trigger pull (~3.5 lbs give or take - may measure it again soon)
3) Gunsmith Fitted (Briley) front bushing
4) Added extended safety
5) Added wider magazine well extension (easily removed).
6) Added an expanded magazine release thumb pad.
7) Titanium firing pin installed (from a series 70).  This disables the series 80 firing pin block plunger - but it can be easily reinstalled and also the series 80 titinium firing pin could be used  thus restoring the firing pin block safety function.  This 3rd trigger safety (after grip and thumb safeties) makes the gun more 'drop safe' -though some say no 1911's have ever fired when dropped anyway).
8) Extended (beavertail) grip safety (to reduce 'slide bite').
9) Lightweight Aluminum trigger (with adjustable stop)
11) Switched to "wrap around" Pachymar rubber grips.  Original checkered wood grips available.
12) Adjustable (ELLISASON) rear sights.
13) (Might have widened the ejection port area a little)
14) Full length guide rod (screws together).  Could swith back to regular recoil spring rod and plug too.
15)Match grade barrel.  Top of slide machined to reduce glare (came stock).

This gun shoots accurately, fast, and flawlessly and does not limit the shooter in any way.

Works flawlessly with all kinds of ammo types.

Lots of magazines come with it ((3) x 11 rounders, (3) x 10 rounders, and (6) x  8  rounders).  The 8 rounders have extended base pads on them.
(Masking tape is on the 11 rounders to indicate their capacity in a glance).
